00:00:00.140 --> 00:00:05.080
Apparently, bacteria have started to become
resistant to antibiotics, so I guess no more

00:00:05.080 --> 00:00:09.080
sewer diving for me!

00:00:09.080 --> 00:00:13.440
Antibiotic resistance is scary.

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:17.869
When bacteria stop responding to antibiotics,
diseases that used to be easily treatable

00:00:17.869 --> 00:00:18.939
can become deadly.

00:00:18.939 --> 00:00:25.750
Each year in the United States alone, at least
23,000 people get infected and die from antibiotic-resistant

00:00:25.750 --> 00:00:26.769
bacteria.

00:00:26.769 --> 00:00:30.539
On previous episodes of DNews we’ve talked
about some of the most threatening types,

00:00:30.539 --> 00:00:35.320
including certain strains of E. coli, MRSA,
which causes staph infections, and Gonorrhea.

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:38.610
Yes, gonorrhea is becoming resistant to medications.

00:00:38.610 --> 00:00:43.340
Clearly antibiotic resistance is a huge problem,
so scientists have been seeking out better,

00:00:43.340 --> 00:00:47.100
more effective treatments to deal with bacteria
that are already resistant.

00:00:47.100 --> 00:00:51.310
To dive into this story, DNews teamed up with
our friends at Seeker Stories to look for

00:00:51.310 --> 00:00:58.040
treatment solutions where we least expect
them: the bottom of the ocean.

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:02.530
Off the coast of California, scientists from
UC-Santa Cruz are scouring the ocean for what

00:01:02.530 --> 00:01:06.549
they hope is the key to fighting a new breed
of drug-resistant superbugs.

